intervene in Vietnam. Relying on interviews with senior officials and on recently declassified documents, the author demonstrates with a precision not attained by previous studies that the three most important analogies of the Vietnam era--Korea, Munich, and Dien Bien Phu--can account for America's Vietnam choices. A special contribution is the author's use of cognitive social psychology to support his argument about how humans analogize and to explain why policymakers often use analogies poorly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInternational relationsxDecision making. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975zUnited States. 7aHISTORY / Military / General.2bisacsh  aAE framework.  aAbelson, Robert.  aBundy, McGeorge.  aBurma.  aChurchill, Winston S.  aEden, Anthony.  aFiske, Susan.  aGelb, Leslie H.  aGeorge, Alexander.  aHanoi.  aIndochina.  aJervis, Robert.  aKennedy, John F.  aKorean War.  aLaos.  aMalayan analogy.  aManchuria.  aMussolini, Benito.  aOperational Code.  aPhilippines.  aappeasement.  acognitive consistency.  acontainment.  adomino theory.  ahistorical analogies.  alessons of Korea.  anuclear weapons.  aprivate use of analogies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691212913zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691212913423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691212913.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK